---
/**
 * ai-agents · 0005 · Figure 7 — recovery escalation ladder: retry → fallback →
 * compensate → escalate, each mapped to a distributed-systems pattern.
 * Verbatim from the source HTML.
 */
---

<figure>
    <svg
        viewBox="0 0 620 196"
        role="img"
        aria-label="An escalation ladder for recovery: retry, then fallback, then compensate, then escalate, each mapped to a distributed systems pattern"
    >
        <g font-family="ui-sans-serif,system-ui,sans-serif">
            <rect
                x="10"
                y="10"
                width="600"
                height="30"
                rx="7"
                fill="#f7ecea"
                stroke="#9a2417"
                stroke-width="1.5"></rect>
            <text
                x="310"
                y="30"
                text-anchor="middle"
                font-size="12"
                font-weight="700"
                fill="#9a2417">A STEP FAILS</text
            >
            <!-- 4 stages -->
            <rect x="12" y="64" width="140" height="76" rx="8" fill="#eef5ee" stroke="#2f5d3a"
            ></rect>
            <text x="82" y="84" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" font-weight="700" fill="#2f5d3a"
                >1 · Retry</text
            >
            <text x="82" y="102" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#111110"
                >transient? backoff</text
            >
            <text x="82" y="116" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#111110"
                >+ jitter, bounded,</text
            >
            <text x="82" y="130" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#111110"
                >idempotent only</text
            >
            <rect x="164" y="64" width="140" height="76" rx="8" fill="#f3f7ec" stroke="#7a8a3f"
            ></rect>
            <text
                x="234"
                y="84"
                text-anchor="middle"
                font-size="11"
                font-weight="700"
                fill="#5c6a2a">2 · Fallback</text
            >
            <text x="234" y="102" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#111110"
                >degrade gracefully:</text
            >
            <text x="234" y="116" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#111110"
                >smaller model /</text
            >
            <text x="234" y="130" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#111110"
                >cache / alt tool</text
            >
            <rect x="316" y="64" width="140" height="76" rx="8" fill="#fbf3e6" stroke="#b07d18"
            ></rect>
            <text
                x="386"
                y="84"
                text-anchor="middle"
                font-size="11"
                font-weight="700"
                fill="#8a5e0f">3 · Compensate</text
            >
            <text x="386" y="102" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#111110"
                >side effect done &amp;</text
            >
            <text x="386" y="116" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#111110"
                >not reversible &rarr;</text
            >
            <text x="386" y="130" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#111110"
                >run an undo action</text
            >
            <rect x="468" y="64" width="142" height="76" rx="8" fill="#f7ecea" stroke="#9a2417"
            ></rect>
            <text
                x="539"
                y="84"
                text-anchor="middle"
                font-size="11"
                font-weight="700"
                fill="#9a2417">4 · Escalate</text
            >
            <text x="539" y="102" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#111110"
                >give up safely:</text
            >
            <text x="539" y="116" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#111110"
                >dead-letter queue</text
            >
            <text x="539" y="130" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#111110">+ human</text>
            <!-- escalation arrows -->
            <line
                x1="152"
                y1="102"
                x2="164"
                y2="102"
                stroke="#9a2417"
                stroke-width="1.4"
                marker-end="url(#arwR)"></line>
            <line
                x1="304"
                y1="102"
                x2="316"
                y2="102"
                stroke="#9a2417"
                stroke-width="1.4"
                marker-end="url(#arwR)"></line>
            <line
                x1="456"
                y1="102"
                x2="468"
                y2="102"
                stroke="#9a2417"
                stroke-width="1.4"
                marker-end="url(#arwR)"></line>
            <!-- analogy chips -->
            <text
                x="82"
                y="160"
                text-anchor="middle"
                font-size="8.5"
                font-style="italic"
                fill="#6b675f">= TCP retransmit</text
            >
            <text
                x="234"
                y="160"
                text-anchor="middle"
                font-size="8.5"
                font-style="italic"
                fill="#6b675f">= graceful degradation</text
            >
            <text
                x="386"
                y="160"
                text-anchor="middle"
                font-size="8.5"
                font-style="italic"
                fill="#6b675f">= Saga pattern</text
            >
            <text
                x="539"
                y="160"
                text-anchor="middle"
                font-size="8.5"
                font-style="italic"
                fill="#6b675f">= DLQ + on-call</text
            >
            <text x="310" y="184" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#9c968a"
                >Climb the ladder only as far as you must &mdash; and wrap every tool in a circuit
                breaker so one sick dependency can't sink the run.</text
            >
        </g>
    </svg>
    <figcaption>
        Recovery is an escalation ladder: cheap-and-local first, expensive-and-human last. The one
        agents get wrong is <em>compensation</em> &mdash; you can't roll back a sent email, so you need
        a defined undo.
    </figcaption>
</figure>
